The influences of George Carlin are evident in his routine and clearly enrich his performance.

I love Bill Maher on his TV show, where he moderates and plays off of other contributors, The "funny" didn't translate in this "stand-uo" in a theatre, solo, for an hour. This set just doesn't work for me. It was too much blather and preaching to the choir than comedy. The hour felt like an agonizing eternity to me, with his posturing and laughing at his political jibes, before he blurted them out. Like it was as if it were an inside joke, but, in reality, while the political observations were accurate, the humor was often missing or simply inadequate for the time he was onstage. There was too much time between "jokes" (observations) that actually had punchlines. Instead of laughing as often I had anticipated, I was just reminded, as nauseum, of how bad a shape we as a citizenry, really are in.
Pretty much go get what you expect.  If you're a fan, worth watching.

Bill Maher has a talent for mixing his comedy routine with political viewpoints. The best part about his content is the fact that he is simply referencing contradictions and hypocrisy derived from hard facts. I enjoy watching his routines.

Though performed and released in 2010, Bill Maher once again makes plenty of good points in But I'm Not Wrong (accurate title too- he's *not* wrong, hardly ever!)  I had a feeling going into this comedy routine that Bill's views on religion are, let's just say, less friendly compared to other views, haha.  He pretty much confirmed where he stands on religious matters on an episode of Jay Leno about a year ago.  He basically describes God and Jesus as fictional characters that people have been making up for over 2,000 years.  Do I agree with this?  Hmmm, haha.  Not really.  Mildly funny regardless though *incredibly* offensive to a person who's deeply religious (and understandably so).

The political side of the routine is sort of dated now.  Sarah Palin, John McCain, the inauguration of Barack Obama, George Bush, Hillary and Bill Clinton... these people are quite the topic of Bill's conversation since they were relevant and newsworthy in 2010.

My feelings overall on Bill Maher after watching this comedy special is that he makes several good points, is very offensive, nearly impossible to disagree with (except concerning the subject of religion of course which has always been debatable) and probably won't become religious any time soon... and neither will I.  However he's only funny about half the time.  Making good points and being funny aren't always one and the same, but humor is a matter of preference anyway.  Recommended for the strong material, but be prepared for several sexual-related content that borders on really strong.

I was at this show, and loved it. Obviously, I am a fan, or I would not have bought tickets.
Interesting thing about the show - it happened on Feb 13, the day after a massive snow storm moved over the entire state. But the show was sold out.
I know some complained about Maher not being as funny as he once was. And though this may be somewhat true, I have to say that I didn't go because I was expecting a laugh a minute evening. Maher isn't exactly a comic anymore. He is a commentator who uses satire to make his points. And I tend to agree with many of them. This wasn't the blue collar comedy tour, this wasn't Robin Williams. This was Bill Maher, doing an extended version of what he does on his HBO show. And that's what I like.

If you like Bill Maher, this DVD is for you. If you don't like Bill Maher but enjoy talking back to a DVD or enjoy being agitated by his views so you can blow off steam to your friends about what he says, this DVD is for you. If you can't stand Bill Maher you might want to buy this DVD anyway just to reinforce your negative attitude towards this clever, irreverant comedian who picks up where George Carlin left off.

He's one of the most intelligent and no-holds-barred comedic commentators of our time.  He's irreverent almost to a fault. If you're at all insulted by an in-your-face review of life as he sees it, Bill Maher will make you gasp.  To his credit, he's usually cuttingly on target and his wit and facial "verbiage" must be heard AND seen to be appreciated. He pushes his comedy to the limit and spares no one. I loved this DVD.  My only reason for giving it four rather than five stars was that he seemed a little forced at times and not as comfortable with his delivery as I expected. Perhaps that's because most of my exposure to Maher has been on his TV shows, where he interacts with other notables and plays off either their intelligence and wit or their stupidity. If you enjoy a great verbal punch, watch this guy put on his discerning mental gloves and start throwing jabs.
